🧠 0. What you THINK you did vs what you ACTUALLY did
What it feels like:

“I wrote a C++ file and somehow it runs”

Reality:

You built a complete software system pipeline

🧱 1. Your code (the core)

File:

src/main.cpp

👉 This is your actual logic

It does:

create server
accept clients
send response
Analogy:

👉 This is like:

engine of a car 🚗

Without this → nothing exists

⚙️ 2. CMake (the builder)

We added:
👉 CMake

File:

CMakeLists.txt
🧠 What CMake does

It answers:

“How do I convert your .cpp into a runnable program?”

Internally:

When you run:

cmake -B build -S .

👉 CMake:

scans src/*.cpp
prepares build instructions
generates build files

Then:

cmake --build build

👉 It:

calls compiler (clang)
compiles code
creates executable
Output:
build/redis

👉 This is your actual program

Analogy:
Component	Real life
CMake	factory manager
Compiler	worker
Executable	finished product
📦 3. vcpkg (dependency manager)

We installed:
👉 vcpkg

🧠 Why needed?

Your project uses:

find_package(asio REQUIRED)

👉 Means:

“I need external library (asio)”

Without vcpkg

You would:

download library manually ❌
configure include paths ❌
debug linking errors ❌
With vcpkg

You wrote:

vcpkg.json

👉 It says:

“I need asio + pthreads”

When you run project

vcpkg:

downloads libraries
builds them
connects them with your project
Analogy:
Component	Real life
vcpkg	Amazon
asio	product
vcpkg.json	shopping list
🔗 4. Integration (CMake + vcpkg)

This line is KEY:

-DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=$VCPKG_ROOT/scripts/buildsystems/vcpkg.cmake
🧠 What it means

You are telling CMake:

“Hey, use vcpkg to find libraries”

Without this:

❌ CMake cannot find asio
❌ build fails

With this:

✔ CMake + vcpkg connected
✔ dependencies resolved automatically

▶️ 5. run.sh (automation script)

File:

run.sh
🧠 What it does

Instead of typing:

cmake -B build -S .
cmake --build build
./build/redis

👉 You just do:

./run.sh
Internally:
Step 1 → configure (CMake)
Step 2 → install deps (vcpkg)
Step 3 → build
Step 4 → run
Analogy:

👉 run.sh = “one button to start everything”

📁 6. Project structure
mini_reddis/
  src/
    main.cpp
  CMakeLists.txt
  run.sh
  vcpkg.json
🧠 Why structure matters
src/ → code
build/ → compiled output
root → configuration

👉 This separation is used in real companies

🔌 7. What happens when you run ./run.sh

Let’s break EXACT flow:

Step 1: vcpkg runs
-- Running vcpkg install

👉 It checks:

do we have asio?
if not → install
Step 2: CMake configure
-- Configuring done

👉 It:

reads CMakeLists
prepares build
Step 3: Build
[100%] Built target redis

👉 Compiler converts .cpp → binary

Step 4: Run program
Redis server starting...

👉 Your code executes

🌐 8. Your server (runtime behavior)

Your program:

socket → bind → listen → accept
🧠 What happens
Server opens port 6379
Waits for clients
Client connects (nc)
Your code handles request
Analogy:
Concept	Real life
socket	phone line
port	phone number
client	caller
server